ce:section.ce:para:
As shown in Scheme 1
                        , fluorescent N-CDs were prepared by facile hydrothermal treatment (200 °C, 10 h) using OC as carbon source, ammonia water as nitrogen passivator and deionized water as solvent without any strong acid, alkali or poisonous agent. In order to get high yield and QY of N-CDs, the mass ratio of OC to nitrogen passivator was optimized (Table 1
                        ). Both yield and QY of N-CDs increased with the increasing mass ratio of OC to nitrogen passivator from 1:0 to 1:15. Further increase of mass ratio of OC to nitrogen passivator from 1:15 to 1:20 did not increase the yield and QY of N-CDs. The yield, QY and solid residue rate of N-CDs at mass ratio 1:15 of OC to nitrogen passivator were 44.0%, 30.3% and 3.8%, respectively. These results were significantly better than those of N-CDs synthesized using dissolving pulp as carbon source which were 2.9%, 9.7% and 74.8% for the yield, QY and residue rate of N-CDs, respectively. With an effort comparing the yield of N-CDs from present study to references [36,37,39,53], it was found that the yield of N-CDs had been rarely reported. This is probably attributed to the low yield of N-CDs from cellulose by previous studies as was proved to be 2.9% from dissolving pulp by our studies. Considering that the yield of OC from dissolving pulp was 36.6%, the overall yield of N-CDs from dissolving pulp associated with oxidization treatment should be 16.1%. Though, this result (16.1%) was significantly higher than that of N-CDs from dissolving pulp (2.9%) without the oxidation treatment. The high yield of N-CDs from OC was attributed the oxidation treatment which increased the accessibility of cellulose, as is shown above.
